INSERT INTO posts (user_id, usr_type_id, name, name_ES, slug, image, content, content_ES, enabled) VALUES (1, 1, 'Diabetics urged to get COVID vaccine following blood clot death', 'Se insta a los diabéticos a recibir la vacuna COVID después de la muerte por coágulos de sangre', 'new4', 'https://static.ffx.io/images/$zoom_0.222%2C$multiply_1.0582%2C$ratio_1.5%2C$width_756%2C$x_0%2C$y_0/t_crop_custom/q_86%2Cf_auto/6b0fc4c18d3a9d3581c8b8a6a3bd9acee4a2c459', 'Diabetics are being encouraged to continue coming forward for the coronavirus vaccine, following news that a 48-year-old woman died after developing a very rare blood clot condition likely linked to her recent AstraZeneca shot.People with type 1 and type 2 diabetes are at increased risk of some types of blood clots, but experts said there is no evidence to suggest they run a greater risk of developing the rare condition believed to be caused by the AstraZeneca vaccine known as thrombosis with thrombocytopenia syndrome (TTS).Central Coast woman Genene Norris, who had several chronic diseases, died last week at John Hunter Hospital after she developed blood clots in the arteries and veins and had a low platelet count.The Therapeutic Goods Administration’s vaccine safety investigation group concluded on Friday that her death was likely linked to the jab, but it remains under investigation because of the unusual clinical profile of the case, the regulator’s head, Professor John Skerritt said.There have been two previously confirmed Australian cases of TTS, and cases number fewer than five per million recipients of the AstraZeneca vaccine in the UK.The condition led vaccine advisory group ATAGI to recommend people under 50 receive the Pfizer vaccine over the AstraZeneca shot, although patient fact sheets distributed by the federal government last week explained these patients can still choose the AstraZeneca vaccine.Adults of any age with diabetes are eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine as part of phase 1b of the national coronavirus vaccine rollout, along with other people who have a number of other health conditions.Professor Skerritt said the only conditions that appear to put people at an increased risk of TTS are heparin-induced thrombocytopenia, which is quite a rare condition, and previous cases of thrombosis and thymocytapenia, which is also rare.“TGA and international medical experts will continue to assess whether there are any other causative factors on an ongoing basis,” Professor Skerritt said in a statement.“The TGA has reviewed a significant amount of international data, and will continue to, but there is currently no evidence of an increased risk with either type 1 or type 2 diabetes.”Professor Stephen Twigg, head of the department of endocrinology at RPA Hospital, said there was no evidence diabetics were of an elevated risk of developing TTS.“Blood clots in diabetes are mainly linked in with artery complications, not vein ones,” Professor Twigg said.“And these venous clots with the AstraZeneca vaccine, which are a much rarer event than we normally see ... they appear to be immune-based.”', 'Se alienta a los diabéticos a que continúen presentando la vacuna contra el coronavirus, luego de la noticia de que una mujer de 48 años murió después de desarrollar una condición de coágulo de sangre muy rara que probablemente esté relacionada con su reciente inyección de AstraZeneca.La condición llevó al grupo asesor de vacunas ATAGI a recomendar que las personas menores de 50 años reciban la vacuna Pfizer en lugar de la vacuna AstraZeneca, aunque las hojas de datos para pacientes distribuidas por el gobierno federal la semana pasada explicaron que estos pacientes aún pueden elegir la vacuna AstraZeneca.Los adultos de cualquier edad con diabetes son elegibles para recibir una vacuna COVID-19 como parte de la fase 1b del lanzamiento nacional de la vacuna contra el coronavirus, junto con otras personas que tienen otras afecciones de salud.El profesor Skerritt dijo que las únicas condiciones que parecen poner a las personas en un mayor riesgo de STT son la trombocitopenia inducida por heparina, que es una condición bastante rara, y los casos previos de trombosis y timocitapenia, que también son raras."La TGA y los expertos médicos internacionales continuarán evaluando si existen otros factores causales de manera continua", dijo el profesor Skerritt en un comunicado."La TGA ha revisado una cantidad significativa de datos internacionales y continuará haciéndolo, pero actualmente no hay evidencia de un mayor riesgo de diabetes tipo 1 o tipo 2".El profesor Stephen Twigg, jefe del departamento de endocrinología del Hospital RPA, dijo que no había evidencia de que los diabéticos tuvieran un riesgo elevado de desarrollar STT."Los coágulos de sangre en la diabetes están relacionados principalmente con complicaciones de las arterias, no de las venas", dijo el profesor Twigg."Y estos coágulos venosos con la vacuna AstraZeneca, que son un evento mucho más raro de lo que normalmente vemos ... parecen tener una base inmunológica".', 1);
